<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-01-16T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-01-16T13:00:00-05:00" n="685" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d685">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">882.01 Foreign Control/13: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Edge</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-01-16T18:00:00+00:00">January 16, 1931—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 16—2:35 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>20. The Counselor of the British Embassy called this afternoon to say
                            that they had received instructions from London to support any
                            representations which we might make to the French Government to secure
                            their cooperation concerning Liberian slavery situation. British Embassy
                            indicated matter was very urgent as it was to be referred to present
                            session of Council of League of Nations.</p>
                        <p>I informed him that no instructions had as yet been received in the
                            matter.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Edge</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>